Short description (Characteristic features of the ITS service category or ITS service) If a vehicle (with an eCall unit on-board) has an accident, in vehicle sensors generate an automated eCall (with the so called MSD - Minimum Set of Data for vehicles) at the EU wide number 112. This call is directed with highest priorities through all Mobile Telecom Networks to the nearest PSAP - Public Service Answering Point and a fast intervention of medical services to the vehicle accident is organised. Field of application (Motorway, federal highways, urban environment....) All road transport networks. Vision (long-term objective pursued with the ITS service category or ITS service) Serve travellers which have a road accident in the best/ fastest way, and keep traffic disturbances and queues resulting from accidents at a minimum possible. Qualitative ITS Goals (qualitative ITS benefit or qualitative ITS effect ) Reduce the time to reach the travellers involved in an accident. (Some countries and cities have specific public service targets with thiss as KPI e.g. less than 20 minutes on average to reach persons involved in emergencies after a call. Qualitative assessment of the barriers and reservations to implementation (Qualitative assessment of the complexity of the implementation (technological, functional, organizational, regulatory), the implementation period and rough estimate of the implementation costs) The main barriers are organisational, technology and functions of the service are well defined for different vehicle types and mobile networks. eCall service in Europe to all customers without restrictions of SIM cards, contracts, vehicle ownership etc.. is a complex organisational matter. This includes: - Vehicle units that generate the emergency call (including the complete MSD) to one single number in Europe 112 in all countries - Mobile Network Operators that attribute the highest priority to eCall data (MSD set) routing in their networks - PSAP - Public Service Answering Points that are certified according to an agreed process scheme and based on the MSD decoding attribute the eCall to the nearest medical service (and possibly the police) at hand and dispatch it accordingly. Regulatory barriers have been solved and the EU MS agreed to mandatory introduction of eCall service in all new vehicles by march 2018 and in all MS by october 2017. Telecom Network regulations w.r.t emergency services are in place. Functional and technological aspects (short description of functionality and technology of the implementation) Funtions of the emergency call - eCall: - Based on sensor inputs the vehicle unit generates the vehicle specific MSD and sends of the Ecall to a single EU wide number - The Mobile Network operator of the "accident area" recognises the eCall and routes the call to the PSAP with the highest data priority - The PSAP handles the eCall, analyses the vehicle MSD, including the exact location of the vehicle and driving direction, etc.. and dispatches the emergency service to the accident location. - emergency services reach the accident location and can support all passengers involved efficiently. Service constraints and limitations (short description of possible limitations or restrictions for the defined ITS service) - Positioning accuracy of the accident location can be limited, and therefore the MSD not precise - Mobile network coverage can be restricted or limited, depending from the accident location

It is expected that, by reducing the response time of the emergency services, the interoperable EU-wide eCall will reduce the number of fatalities in the Union as well as the severity of injuries caused by road accidents.
The interoperable EU-wide eCall is also expected to bring savings to society by improving incident management and by reducing road congestion and secondary accidents.

UML:Class.name: ensure that personal data are protected against misuse

UML:TaggedValue.value:
The PSAPs, including eCall PSAPs, shall be regarded as data controllers within the meaning of Article 2(d) of Directive 95/46/EC. Where the eCall data is to be sent to other emergency control centres or service partners pursuant to Article 3(5), the latter shall also be considered as data controllers. Member States shall ensure that the processing of personal data in the context of the handling of the eCalls by the PSAPs, the emergency services and service partners is carried out in accordance with Directives 95/46/EC and 2002/58/EC, and that this compliance is demonstrated to the national data protection authorities.
In particular, Member States shall ensure that personal data are protected against misuse, including unlawful access, alteration or loss, and that protocols concerning personal data storage, retention duration, processing and protection are established at the appropriate level and properly observed.

The eCall PSAP shall handle eCalls as expeditiously and effectively as any other call made to the single European emergency number 112. The eCall PSAP shall process eCalls in line with the requirements of national regulations for emergency call processing.

The eCall PSAP shall have access to an appropriate Geographical Information System (GIS) or an equivalent system allowing the eCall PSAP operator to identify the position and heading of the vehicle to a minimum degree of accuracy as defined in EN 15722 for the MSD coordinates

Member States shall ensure that this compliance is demonstrated, with national data protection authorities, either during a priori control procedures, such as prior notifications or a posteriori checks, such as in the course of complaints and investigations.

Article 26 of Directive 2002/22/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council of 7 March 2002 on universal service and users’ rights relating to electronic communications networks and services (Universal Service Directive) (2) requires that calls to the single European emergency call number 112 are answered appropriately and handled in a manner that is best suited to the national organisation of emergency systems, including the emergency call response centres (public safety answering points).

Member States shall ensure that any eCall PSAP is equipped to handle eCalls and receive the MSD originating from the in-vehicle equipment according to the standards ‘Intelligent transport system — eSafety — PanEuropean eCall-Operating requirements’ (EN 16072) and ‘Intelligent transport systems — eSafety — eCall High Level Application Requirements (HLAP)’ (EN 16062).

The eCall PSAP (initially receiving the eCall) shall establish audio communication with the vehicle and handle the eCall data; if necessary, the eCall PSAP may reroute the call and MSD data to another PSAP, emergency control centre or service partner according to national procedures determined by the national authority. Rerouting may be done via data or audio connection, or, preferably, both.

‘service partner’ means a public or private organisation recognised by national authorities, that has a role in the handling of incidents related to an eCall (e.g. road operator, assistance service);

‘eCall transaction’ means the establishment of a mobile wireless communications session across a public wireless communications network and the transmission of a minimum set of data from a vehicle to an eCall PSAP and the establishment of an audio channel between the vehicle and the same eCall PSAP;
‘raw MSD’ means a representation of the transmitted minimum set of data before being presented in an intelligible way to the eCall PSAP operator.
‘eCall PSAP operator’ means a person in the eCall PSAP receiving and/or handling the emergency calls;

Member States shall designate the authorities that are competent for assessing the conformity of the operations of the eCall PSAPs with the requirements listed in Article 3 and shall notify them to the Commission. Conformity assessment shall be based on the part of the standard ‘Intelligent transport systems — eSafety — eCall end to end conformance testing’ (EN 16454) that relates to PSAPs conformance to pan-European eCall.

This Data Store shall be used within the Provide Security and Emergency Facilities Functional Area. It shall contain information objects that provide details of each Public Service Access Point (PSAP) that is able to respond to eCall messages from Vehicles.
Each information object in the store shall contain the following data objects: (1) PSAP name (character string), (2) PSAP identity (number - optional), (3) geographic location of the PSAP (co-ordinates), (4) geographic area from which the PSAP can respond to eCall messages (co-ordinates), (5) type(s) of service available from the PSAP, (6) communication information for the PSAP.
